    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-05-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-05-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="618"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d618">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.5431/181</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the Swiss
                        Minister</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Peter</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-05-09">May 9,
                            1935</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to the proposed trade agreement
                    negotiations between the American Government and the Swiss Government, I have
                    the honor to attach hereto for transmission to your Government a list of
                    products exported from the United States,<note n="7" xml:id="d618fn7">Not
                        printed.</note> on which concessions are requested by the American
                    Government. It is understood that a list of products on which concessions are
                    desired of the United States by your Government will be handed today to the
                    American Minister at Berne by the appropriate Swiss authorities.<note n="8"
                        xml:id="d618fn8">By telegram No. 20, May 10, from the Minister in
                        Switzerland, the Department was informed that the desiderata had been
                        received by the Legation on May 9 (611.5431/178).</note> The general
                    provisions of the proposed agreement to be suggested by the American Government
                    have already been submitted informally to you.</p>
                <p>It is my hope that following this exchange of desiderata between the two
                    Governments early discussions may take place looking to the conclusion of a
                    mutually satisfactory trade agreement.</p>
                <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>For the Secretary of State:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Francis B. Sayre</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
